<TITLE> Indian protests against Wal-Mart fail to ignite </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Aug 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A few hundred Indian traders and small shopkeepers took to streets around the country on Thursday to protest against the arrival of US retail giant Wal-Mart, but a planned nationwide day of action fizzled out. Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and India's Bharti Enterprises this week signed a delayed agreement to jointly set up a chain of wholesale outlets. The entry of foreign retailers, and even the establishment of supermarkets by India's Reliance Industries Ltd. , has been opposed by some political groups and traders who see them as a threat to their livelihoods. "Wal-Mart, Down, Down", "Wal-Mart, Go Back", a crowd of about 200 people shouted in Chandni Chowk, a bustling Delhi market. Later, they burnt a dummy meant to represent Wal-Mart. Other protests took place in Ranchi in eastern India, where some traders threatened to ransack any new private retail outlets, and Bhopal in central India, where a strike called by communists was partially successful. "The government policies are today corporate policies," said activist Vandana Shiva, who led the New Delhi protest. "It's the 'raj' (rule) of Reliance and Wal-Mart." She said large companies would make the Indian farmer dependent on them for purchases. India's retail industry, valued at nearly $350 billion, is forecast to double in size by 2015, with modern retail's share of that expected to rise rapidly from about three percent now. India limits multiple-brand retailers like Wal-Mart to wholesale, and franchise dea
